<br>
There's been a ton of great advice offered by Chuck, John, and Allen.  I'd like to throw in one more bit.<br>
<br>
Please realize that every rod will have a point of overload.  The SLT is not a power rod.  Yes, it is made of ultra-high modulus material.  But the configuration of the tube is such that the rod is not inherently stiff.  Here's a little engineering mechanics class:<br>
<br>
Most flyfishers don't realize there is a difference between stiffness and recovery rate of a rod.  Stiffness is usually referred to in terms of the rod being soft or stiff.  This is a STATIC measurement of how much deflection the rod tip will exhibit when a certain weight (load) is suspended from the tip.  Say for example, you hang a 4 oz weight from a horizontal rod, and the tip sags 6 inches from its neutral (unloaded) position.  Then you take another rod of the same length and line weight, and repeat the test.  This rod deflects 14&quot;.  We would say that the second rod is softer than the first.<br>
<br>
The other way to look at rods relates to how quickly a rod will return from it's fully bent condition, to the neutral condition when the load is removed.  This is where we hear the fast/slow spectrum.  This is a DYNAMIC concept.  The rate of unloading is time dependent, whereas in the previous paragraph, the stiffness test has no bearing on the time that it takes you to apply the load.  <br>
<br>
For obvious reasons, neither stiffness, nor recovery rate can tell the whole story about how a rod will actually cast by a human being.  You have to put the rod in your hand and learn what the rod likes.<br>
<br>
Sectional stiffness is a function of the Youngs modulus of the material, as well as the first moment of inertia (which is, in turn, a function of the geometry of the rod's cross section).  What that means is that you can make a very stiff rod from a soft material -- if you use enough of it.  Just make a large diameter tube, and have lots of wall thickness.  It'll be a telephone pole.  But once you have it bent, and then remove the load -- you'll find that it returns to a straight line quite slowly.  This has to do with both the inertial characteristics (self-weight), and the spring rate of the material.  <br>
<br>
On the other hand, you can construct a very thin-walled, small diameter tube from 65 mpsi material, and it will feel noticeably soft.  But when you remove the load, it will spring back to neutral very, very quickly.  This can honestly be called a fast action, even though it might fully load to the grip with only 30 feet of line out.  <br>
<br>
Most people think that a fast rod and a stiff rod are the same thing, but they are not necessarily.  Many are, but I'll give you an example of a rod that doesn't follow that rule.  Sage's SLT.  It is the followup to the SP series, which exhibited a similar casting characteristic.  They excel at casting quick, accurate loops to targets at moderate distances.  They are not &quot;full fly line&quot; rods in most people's hands -- they were built for a different purpose.  <br>
<br>
Think about this.  Let's say that you've made a backcast.  For the sake of argument, let's even say that it's a perfect 60 foot backcast, smooth, and tight when it has fully unrolled.  Now we're ready to begin to pull this line into motion.  A rod that is very stiff will be able to transmit the caster's input energy to the flyline more directly than a softer rod could.  The softer rod will deflect more when the caster pulls the cork, but the line wants to stay put (inertia).  This deflection can be excessive with a softer rod and a heavy load, and lead to the rod &quot;caving in&quot; and tracing a concave rod tip path.  Of course, we all know that this leads to the undesirable tailing loop.<br>
<br>
So if you take a soft rod (SLT), try to aggressively pull a very long carried line (60+ feet) into motion, guess what happens?  I'm betting that you are getting very close to the limit of your combined equipment.  <br>
<br>
There are a couple possible fixes to see if this is the culprit.  If you have a 4 weight line, put it on and see how it casts.  Most people think in terms of going up in line weight to get more distance, but with a given rod, you can carry more line in the air if you underline, than if you overline.  The rod is only capable of withstanding so much load before it overloads.<br>
<br>
Another possible fix is to to dramatically lengthen your casting stroke.  Stay with me for a minute here.  If you study slo-mo video (I've spent more time and money than I should've doing exactly that), you'll see that a rod can be prevented from overload, if you lengthen the stroke distance so that you can get up to your final speed more gradually.  If you only give yourself 3 feet of tip movement to get to final speed, then you'll really have to accelerate hard and early or you'll never get enough energy into the flyline.  If you give yourself 8 feet of tip movement, it may be better, but still might try to tail on you a little.  Give yourself 12 feet, and you can watch all the shock waves, and tails go away while still transmitting all the energy that the loop needs to unroll all the way.<br>
<br>
Most instructors teach that people should make their strokes as compact as possible.  I don't.  I try to get them to see how little input energy they can put in, and still get the loop to unroll.  I ask them to cast with a very long stroke.  This does not imply that they need to cast with a wide ARC.  No matter how long the stroke length is, the tip still needs to travel in the absolute straightest line you can muster.  The older I get, the more I appreciate Lefty's casting style.<br>
<br>
If you look back on the FFFCCI list archive you will find a reply I made to a post about how to get people to quit tailing.  I described two methods that have worked well for me for many years.  First, I ask them to PULL the line into motion.  A pulling motion uses constrictor muscles, which are much more refined and controllable than extensor muscles which are what we use to push with.  An open stroke allows more pulling than a compact stroke which is mostly a pushing motion.  The second point is to ask the student to &quot;sweet talk the line into coming with you early in the stroke&quot;.  Once you get the line moving, then you can more aggressively accelerate it as you approach the stop.  These two points have really connected with my students over the last ten years, so I keep using them.<br>
<br>
Let me make one last comment.  This is all pretty &quot;high level&quot; stuff.  I usually don't talk to students in this language, but I will with you since I know you're an instructor, and I know you're technical yourself.  As long as we're on the same wavelength, I'd rather use the most direct and descriptive communication possible.  If anything here is unclear, please let me know and I'll try to rephrase.<br>
<br>
Hopefully we'll get to cast together at Conclave, Robert.  I know we could learn things from each other, and I'd jump at the chance.  If it's really important for you to cast a full fly line with a 5 weight, then get yourself a TCR.  But you'll probably want to tame it with a 6 or 7 to actually fish with it...   <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Best regards -- TAM <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=flysoup>flysoup</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 22<br> <font color=#000000>(9/22/03 7:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=30.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Limits on Distance</span><hr size=1> Bravo TROY,<br>
